| Category | Findings |
| --- | --- |
| Patterns | **Dependency Injection (IoC):** `Program.cs` registers `InMemoryData` and controllers via container; constructors receive `InMemoryData` (Admissions/Learning/Alumni controllers).<br>**Repository (in-memory):** `Data/InMemoryData.cs` acts as a coarse repository/Unit-of-Work facade holding collections and seed data, but lacks interfaces or persistence abstraction.<br>**MVC Controllers:** ASP.NET attribute-routed controllers (`AdmissionsController`, `LearningController`, `AlumniController`) expose REST endpoints.<br>**DTO/Entity Models:** 30 POCO classes in `Models/DomainModels.cs` function as DTOs/entities.<br>**Inheritance (Student hierarchy):** `Undergraduate`, `Postgraduate`, `ResearchFellow` extend `Student` for specialization. |
| Abstractions vs Concrete | **Interfaces/Abstract types:** None present; all types are concrete. `Student` is concrete (not abstract) despite subclasses.<br>**Concrete implementations:** 34 concrete classes total (30 models, 3 controllers, 1 data store). Controllers are tightly coupled to `InMemoryData` singleton. |
| SOLID / Decoupling Grade | **Grade: C** — Some DI usage improves testability, but absence of interfaces, service layer, or repository contracts couples controllers directly to data storage. Single Responsibility blurred in `InMemoryData` (seed + storage). Open/Closed and Liskov not enforced due to lack of abstractions; Interface Segregation / Dependency Inversion not applied. |
| Pattern Density | Patterns Found: 5 (DI, Repository, MVC, DTO, Inheritance) / Total Classes: 34 ⇒ **0.15 (15%)**. |
| Notable Gaps | No domain services, validation, or persistence abstractions; no observers/events; no factories/strategies; no unit tests. |
| Recommendations | Introduce repository/service interfaces and register via DI; make `Student` abstract if meant as base; separate seed data from repository; add application services to decouple controllers from data; consider observers for domain events. |
